answers.body_markdown:
The Kibana Discovery uses a Lucene Syntax (Lucene is the search engine/technology Elasticsearch is built on) to let you query your data. However when you send requests via the DevTool you basically call the **Elasticsearch REST API**. You can **not** use the Lucene syntax there.

Your second match query is the problem:

I assume you want to search for exact matches (command == HEARTBEAT; charging == 0). But with the match query you are doing a **fulltext search** on the fields.

Instead of the match query you need to use the [term query][1]. So after the first match query you would define two term queries (one for the command field and one for the charging field) inside the must-clause. Notice that when using the **must** clause it automatically applies an AND-operator on all queries inside it.

This is how your query could look like (untested):

    GET filebeat-*/_search
    {
      &quot;size&quot;: 1000,
      &quot;query&quot;: {
        &quot;bool&quot;: {
          &quot;must&quot;: [
            {
              &quot;match&quot;: {
                &quot;log.file.path&quot;: &quot;MYlog&quot;
              }
            },
            {
              &quot;term&quot;: {
                &quot;command&quot;: {
                  &quot;value&quot;: &quot;HEARTBEAT&quot;
                }
              }
            },
            {
              &quot;term&quot;: {
                &quot;charging&quot;: {
                  &quot;value&quot;: 0
                }
              }
            }
          ],
          &quot;filter&quot;: {
            &quot;range&quot;: {
              &quot;@timestamp&quot;: {
                &quot;gte&quot;: &quot;now-15m&quot;
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }

Alternatively you can search on the command.**keyword** field.


  [1]: https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/query-dsl-term-query.html

